              "Description": "Isopentane is used in Ormat Energy Converters (OECs) as part of the process of generating electricity from geothermal fluid.  Each Plant East Mesa (PEM) Unit at the East Mesa Geothermal Projects is considered one covered process.  There are four (4) PEM Units using isopentane at the East Mesa Geothermal Projects.  The PHA information presented here addresses all four PEM Units and therefore all covered processes.  In the electricity generation process, geothermal fluid is routed to an individual OEC.  Isopentane is vaporized via non-contact heat exchange from the hot geothermal fluid.  The isopentane vapor is then used as the motive fluid to spin the OEC generator, generating electricity.  Isopentane vapor is then condensed back to liquid.  The isopentane process is a closed loop process in each OEC.  Each PEM Unit also has one typically full storage tank of isopentane, and one or two normally empty tanks that are used during maintenance on the OEC units.",
